  1. Which state has the least average percentage difference between the high and low estimates of the reported pesticide usage? Entries with no low etimates should be excluded.
pest.total %>%
  filter(!is.na(LOW_ESTIMATE)) %>%
  group_by(STATE_CODE) %>%
  summarise(sum.high = sum(HIGH_ESTIMATE), sum.low = sum(LOW_ESTIMATE)) %>%
  mutate(mean_est = mean(c(sum.high, sum.low)), 
         abs.difference = sum.high - sum.low, 
         perc.difference = (100*abs.difference/mean_est)) %>%
  filter(perc.difference == max(perc.difference))

  1. When is the most dangerous time to drive? Find the hour of the day that has the highest occurance of fatal accidents, normalized by the total number of accidents that occured in that hour (compute the corresponding frequency of fatal accidents to all accidents in that hour). Note: round accident times down. For example, if an accident occured at 23:55 it occured in hour 23
accidents$Time <- hour(strptime(accidents$Time, format = "%H:%M"))
casualties %>%

  1. Is there a linear treand in the number of accidents that occured each year? Return the slope in units of increased number of accidents per year
accidents$Date <- as.numeric(str_sub(accidents$Date, 7))

accidents.per.year <- accidents %>% group_by(Date) %>% summarise(accidents = n())
lm(accidents ~ Date, accidents.per.year)

  1. How fast do the number of car accidents drop off with age? Only consider car drivers who are legally allowed to drive in the UK (17 years and older). Find the rate at which the number of accidents exponentially decays with age. Age is measured in years. Assume that the number of accidents is exponentially distributed with age for the drivers over the age of 17?
accidents.by.age <- vehicles %>%
  filter(Age_of_Driver > 16) %>% ## Remove drivers too young to legally drive
  group_by(Age_of_Driver) %>%
  summarise(n.accidents = n())
accidents.by.age %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = log(n.accidents), x = Age_of_Driver)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + geom_point()

summary(lm(formula = log(n.accidents) ~ Age_of_Driver, data = accidents.by.age))

  1. How many times more likely are you to be in an accident where you skid, jackknife, or overturn (as opposed to an accident where you don’t) when it’s raining or snowing compared to nice weather with no high winds? Ignore accients where the weather is unknown or missing
bad.weather <- c(2, 3, 5, 6) ## the codes for rain and snow in no wind (2, 3) and high wind (5, 6)
good.weather <- 1 ## code for fine weather no high wind
spec.accident <- c(1:5) ## The specified accidents (skid, jackknife, overturn)

accidents %>%
  right_join(vehicles, by = "Accident_Index") %>%
  mutate(binary.weather = ifelse(Weather_Conditions == good.weather, yes = 0, ## create a new variable, binary.weather, which indicates if the weather is fair (0) or in the list (1) else (2) to be removed.
                                 no = ifelse(Weather_Conditions %in% bad.weather, yes = 1, 
                                        no = 2)), 
         binary.accident = ifelse(Skidding_and_Overturning %in% spec.accident, yes = 1, no = 0)) %>% # create a new var, binary.accident, that indicates if the accident was one specified (1) or a different kind of accident (0)
  filter(binary.weather != 2) %>% #removes weather conditions that don't match our expectations
  group_by(binary.weather, binary.accident) %>%
  summarise(n.accidents = n()) %>% group_by(binary.weather) %>% ## Total number of accidents grouped by weather condition and accident type
  summarise(probability = n.accidents[2]/n.accidents[1]) %>% ## calculate the probability of having a specified accident grouped by weather
  ungroup() %>% summarise(times.as.likely = probability[2]/probability[1]) ## calculate how many more times likely you are to be in that accident depending on the weather
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   times.as.likely
##             <dbl>
## 1            1.99
